This paper discusses the challenges of incentivizing online privacy through transparency in the context of the German health insurance market. It involves the use of privacy-enhancing technologies and regulatory measures, which are typically studied in the sub-category of cs.CR (Cryptography and Security). The study also involves the assessment of websites using PrivacyScore.org, which falls under the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society). The paper also touches upon issues related to user behavior and attitudes towards privacy, which could be classified under cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). Additionally, the study involves the evaluation of the health insurance market, which could be categorized under cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) or cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
